## The figure-8 in the rotating frame and teardrop in the inertial frame

In the **co-rotating (synodic) frame** where the Earth-Moon line is frozen, the free-return trajectory traces a **figure-8**: one large loop around Earth and one smaller loop around the Moon, connected at a crossing point on the Earth-Moon axis. The spacecraft moves **clockwise** (viewed from above the north pole) — retrograde relative to the Moon's orbital direction. It departs Earth on one side of the Earth-Moon line, crosses to the Moon's far side, loops behind the Moon, crosses back, and returns. The crossing of the Earth-Moon line creates the characteristic pinch point.

In the **inertial frame**, the same trajectory appears as an elongated, teardrop-shaped loop. The spacecraft follows a highly eccentric Earth orbit that gets gravitationally deflected near the Moon. There is no figure-8 — that's an artifact of the rotating frame "freezing" the Moon's position.

The relationship between frames is a time-dependent rotation. If (x, y) are rotating-frame coordinates and (X, Y) are inertial coordinates, with ω = 1 in non-dimensional units and t as time:

**Position**: `X = x·cos(t) − y·sin(t)`, `Y = x·sin(t) + y·cos(t)`

**Velocity** (includes the transport theorem correction): `Ẋ = (ẋ − y)·cos(t) − (ẏ + x)·sin(t)`, `Ẏ = (ẋ − y)·sin(t) + (ẏ + x)·cos(t)`

The inverse: `x = X·cos(t) + Y·sin(t)`, `y = −X·sin(t) + Y·cos(t)`, and `ẋ = Ẋ·cos(t) + Ẏ·sin(t) + y`, `ẏ = −Ẋ·sin(t) + Ẏ·cos(t) − x`.

