## CR3BP equations of motion: the complete formulation

The CR3BP uses a **barycentric rotating frame** with non-dimensional units where the Earth-Moon distance = 1, the frame angular velocity ω = 1, and the total mass = 1. The single governing parameter is the **mass ratio μ = M_moon/(M_earth + M_moon) ≈ 0.01215**. Earth sits at (−μ, 0) and the Moon at (1−μ, 0).

Define distances to each body:

```
σ = √[(x + μ)² + y²]       (distance to Earth)
ψ = √[(x − 1 + μ)² + y²]   (distance to Moon)
```

The **equations of motion** (2D planar, ready for numerical integration):

```
ẍ =  2ẏ + x − (1−μ)(x+μ)/σ³ − μ(x−1+μ)/ψ³
ÿ = −2ẋ + y − (1−μ)y/σ³     − μy/ψ³
```

The terms decompose as: **2ẏ and −2ẋ** are Coriolis acceleration (from the rotating frame); **x and y** on the right-hand side are centrifugal acceleration; the remaining terms are gravitational attraction from Earth and Moon respectively.

The **Jacobi constant** — the only conserved quantity — serves as a numerical accuracy check:

```
C = (x² + y²) + 2(1−μ)/σ + 2μ/ψ − (ẋ² + ẏ²)
```

This should remain constant throughout integration. Drift in C signals insufficient integrator precision.

