## Patched conics vs. CR3BP vs. full ephemeris

| Aspect | Patched conics | CR3BP | Full ephemeris |
|--------|---------------|-------|----------------|
| Fidelity | **Poor for lunar** — Moon's SOI (~66,000 km) spans 1/6 of the Earth-Moon distance | Good for preliminary design | Mission-grade |
| Physics captured | Two-body segments stitched at SOI | Simultaneous gravity of both bodies, Lagrange points, manifolds | Real orbits, Sun, J2, everything |
| Complexity | Analytical (simplest) | ~20 lines of ODE code | Requires ephemeris files (DE440) |
| **Best for** | Conceptual understanding | **Educational visualization** | Actual mission planning |

For a web visualization, **CR3BP is the clear winner**. It captures the essential three-body dynamics that produce the figure-8, runs fast enough for real-time animation, and the equations fit in a single function. Patched conics miss the continuous gravitational interplay that makes the trajectory beautiful and physically interesting. Full ephemeris is overkill and adds complexity without visual benefit.

One caveat: for multi-day trajectories, the **Sun's gravity is non-negligible** — a Space Stack Exchange discussion of free-return simulations confirmed that omitting it causes trajectory degradation. For a visualization, this matters less (the qualitative shape is correct), but for quantitative accuracy, the Sun's tidal effect can be added as a perturbation.

