## Practical visualization architecture

The recommended approach for a 2D interactive web visualization:

**Pre-compute the trajectory** at startup using RK4 integration, storing the full state array. Then animate playback by stepping through the array — this avoids frame drops from real-time integration. Two side-by-side HTML5 Canvas panels show the rotating frame (figure-8) and inertial frame (teardrop) simultaneously.

The main challenge is **scale**: LEO radius (0.017) is 60× smaller than the Earth-Moon distance (1.0). Solutions include drawing Earth and Moon at exaggerated radii for visibility, and providing a zoom control or inset view near Earth for the departure/arrival phase.

For the Arenstorf orbit, integrate for exactly one period T ≈ 17.065 to get a closed loop. For the LEO injection version, integrate for ~6 non-dimensional time units. Draw zero-velocity curves (contours of the Jacobi constant) as background context to show the energy landscape and Lagrange point gateways. Bold the spacecraft's current position and draw a fading trail showing the recent path.

